In my recent project, I worked on a cloud-native Pooja Booking Application built using a microservices architecture. The application consisted of 8 backend microservices and 2 frontend portals — an Admin Portal and a User Portal.

The frontend applications were developed using ReactJS, and the backend services were developed in NodeJS. Each microservice and frontend application had its own dedicated Git repository, so overall we managed multiple repositories with separate CI/CD pipelines for each service.

For CI/CD automation, I implemented GitHub Actions pipelines. Whenever code was pushed to the development branch, the pipeline was triggered automatically.

For backend services, the pipeline flow was designed as follows:

First, the application code went through SonarQube analysis for code quality and security checks.
After successful validation, the Docker image was built.
Each image was tagged using the Git commit ID for proper version tracking and rollback support.
The Docker image was then scanned using Trivy to identify vulnerabilities.
After successful scanning, the image was digitally signed using Cosign for image authenticity and supply chain security.
The signed image was pushed to Amazon ECR.
Once the image was available in ECR, the pipeline automatically updated the ECS Task Definition with the new image version.
A new ECS task definition revision was created, and then the ECS service was updated to deploy the latest version.

For frontend applications, the pipeline process was slightly different:

The ReactJS application was built through GitHub Actions.
The generated build artifacts were uploaded to Amazon S3 buckets configured for static website hosting.
After deployment, a CloudFront cache invalidation was triggered automatically so users could immediately access the latest frontend changes without stale cache issues.
Route 53 was used for DNS management.

The complete backend infrastructure was hosted on Amazon ECS. The frontend and backend communication was handled through CloudFront and Application Load Balancer (ALB), which provided secure and scalable routing.

We also implemented several AWS services for storage, security, and scalability:

Used Amazon S3 for storing application data and media files.
Configured pre-signed URLs for secure upload and download operations.
Created private S3 access URLs used securely within the application.
Stored sensitive credentials and secrets in AWS Secrets Manager.
Used PostgreSQL as the primary database.
Implemented RabbitMQ for asynchronous communication between microservices.
Configured AWS WAF to protect the application from common web attacks.

For infrastructure optimization, the ECS task definitions for development and production environments were configured differently based on resource requirements. Additionally, to optimize AWS costs, the development ECS services were scheduled to run only during working hours and automatically stopped after office hours.

Apart from CI/CD and deployment automation, I was also involved in infrastructure provisioning, monitoring, troubleshooting deployment issues, security improvements, and overall DevOps process enhancements for the project.






